properties.documentation:
Abstract entity that reflects the intellectual content of an Asset and represents those characteristics that are independent of its physical embodiment.
Source: ADMS-AP
The rule or principle used to judge, evaluate or assess something. The Criterion class has the properties described below.

An application profile customises one or more existing specifications potentially for a given use case or a policy domain adding an end to end narrative describing and ensuring the interoperability of its underlying specification(s).

The narrative of how a given specification or a set of specifications is applied for a particular use case. Additional information:
  • A specification can be configured for one specific application in a given context or domain. For example, each NATO profile is a family of specifications that has been configured with a very particular application in mind.
A collection of interrelated and/or complementary specifications, standards or application profiles and the explanation of how they are combined, used or both.
Area of requirements addressed by the specification.

documentation.value: This property contains the main identifier for the scope, e.g. the URI or another unique identifier.
This property contains a free-text account of the Scope. This property can be repeated for parallel language versions of the description.

properties.documentation:
Set of agreed, descriptive and normative statements about how an specification should be designed or made. Additional information:
  • Statements may take the form of principles, requirements, recommendations and non-normative diagrams and examples, etc.
  • A specification can be related to activities (e.g. procedure document, process specification and test specification), or products (e.g. product specification, performance specification and drawing).
Source: ISO standard (ISO 9000:200518), used by EIRA

documentation.value: This property contains the main identifier for the specification, e.g. the URI or another unique identifier.
The name given to the Specification.
The alternative name of the specification.
This property contains a free-text account of the Specification. This property can be repeated for parallel language versions of the description.
This property refers to the type of the Specification. A controlled vocabulary for the values has not been defined for the time being. A proposal is provided in the examples below.
The entity primarily responsible for making the specification.

properties.documentation: Specification that is largely adopted and possibly endorsed.

List of use cases, contexts or domains for which a specification or a family of specifications are used or configured. Additional information:
  • Example 1 (related to Application Profile): The European Application Profile of the Core Public Service Vocabulary (CPSV-AP); The CAMSS Application Profile of the CAV.
  • Example 2 (related to families): The list of the different use cases for which NATO defines one or more family configurations.
Note that the descendants of the specifications are all disjoint.

Abstract component that captures architecture requirements and that directs and guides the development of Solution Building Blocks.
An ABB represents a (potentially re-usable) component of legal, organisational, semantic or technical capability that can be combined with other Architecture Building Blocks. An Architecture Building Block describes generic characteristics and functionalities. Architecture Building Blocks are used to describe reference architectures, solution architecture templates or solution architectures of a specific solutions.
(Source EIRA, Based on TOGAF)
Concrete element that defines the implementation and fulfils the required business requirements of one or more Architecture Building Blocks.

Document containing agreed normative statements for solution building blocks used in an information exchange context.
Additional information: It can refer to existing standards or specifications. An Interoperability Specification realises an Interoperability Requirement.
All things described by RDF are called resources, and are instances of the class rdfs:Resource. This is the class of everything. All other classes are subclasses of this class.

documentation.value:
<u>configuredIn</u>: A set of Specifications potentially for a given use case or policy domain that are aggregated in an ApplicationProfile.
<u>configures:</u> Whether an Application Profile design or adapts a Specification for a specific purpose.

An instance of a family, either configured or not, becomes a specification per se. Additional information:
  • This allows amongst other things to create ELIS catalogs of ABBs linked to families of specifications.

Combines: Whether a Family is a union of more than one Specifications.
Combined In: A set of Specifications that are complementary and interrelated, forming a Family of Specifications.
